1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:02,537
104 commits.

2
00:00:02,487 --> 00:00:04,637
Eight repositories.

3
00:00:04,637 --> 00:00:07,325
Zero user-facing features.

4
00:00:07,325 --> 00:00:09,487
Best day we've had.

5
00:00:09,487 --> 00:00:11,525
Jake's Daily Build.

6
00:00:11,525 --> 00:00:13,275
What we built.

7
00:00:13,275 --> 00:00:14,925
What broke.

8
00:00:14,925 --> 00:00:16,775
What I learned.

9
00:00:16,775 --> 00:00:18,925
This is The Mega Day.

10
00:00:18,925 --> 00:00:23,612
There's a trap in software where you always feel like you should be shipping features.

11
00:00:23,612 --> 00:00:25,787
Features are visible.

12
00:00:25,787 --> 00:00:28,275
Features feel like progress.

13
00:00:28,275 --> 00:00:34,000
But some days the best move is to stop building the product and build the system that builds the product.

14
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:37,587
Yesterday, every commit was infrastructure.

15
00:00:37,587 --> 00:00:39,950
Nothing a user would see.

16
00:00:39,950 --> 00:00:43,300
And it changed how fast we move going forward.

17
00:00:43,300 --> 00:00:45,925
It started with a shopping spree.

18
00:00:45,925 --> 00:00:48,950
Ten agent skills installed in an hour.

19
00:00:48,950 --> 00:00:55,887
A marketing framework with 23 modules — launch strategy, pricing psychology, conversion optimization.

20
00:00:55,887 --> 00:00:59,275
Document generators for PowerPoint and Word.

21
00:00:59,275 --> 00:01:01,575
A go-to-market playbook.

22
00:01:01,575 --> 00:01:05,687
A security vetting protocol for evaluating new tools.

23
00:01:05,687 --> 00:01:11,925
Why this matters: when you tell an AI agent "plan the product launch," it generates generic advice.

24
00:01:11,925 --> 00:01:21,412
When the same agent has a structured launch framework loaded — phased rollout, channel selection, owned versus rented audience — it generates a plan with actual methodology.

25
00:01:21,412 --> 00:01:23,837
The knowledge isn't in the model.

26
00:01:23,837 --> 00:01:27,550
It's in the skill files the model reads before working.

27
00:01:27,550 --> 00:01:31,662
We wrote product-marketing-context files for three projects.

28
00:01:31,662 --> 00:01:37,262
One file per product — positioning, competitors, audience, pricing, gaps.

29
00:01:37,262 --> 00:01:40,162
Every marketing skill reads it first.

30
00:01:40,162 --> 00:01:50,112
Ask the agent to write landing page copy and it already knows the product is privacy-first, the accent color is purple, and the competitor weakness is that Discord harvests data.

31
00:01:50,112 --> 00:01:52,975
That led to brand guidelines as code.

32
00:01:52,975 --> 00:01:54,712
Two files.

33
00:01:54,712 --> 00:02:00,025
One for our workspace — terracotta on near-black, system fonts, direct voice.

34
00:02:00,025 --> 00:02:04,687
One for our chat product — purple accent, playful but trustworthy.

35
00:02:04,687 --> 00:02:06,700
Agent-readable.

36
00:02:06,700 --> 00:02:11,412
Sub-agents pull the right brand file when building UI or writing copy.

37
00:02:11,412 --> 00:02:14,862
No more "why is this purple when our brand is red.

38
00:02:14,862 --> 00:02:18,525
Then the cleanup nobody asks for but everyone needs.

39
00:02:18,525 --> 00:02:22,550
Five repositories renamed to remove identity leakage.

40
00:02:22,550 --> 00:02:25,250
All local directories renamed.

41
00:02:25,250 --> 00:02:30,200
Four systemd units migrated — stop, rename, update, restart.

42
00:02:30,200 --> 00:02:32,750
Zero downtime per service.

43
00:02:32,750 --> 00:02:36,325
GitHub's automatic redirects meant nothing broke.

44
00:02:36,325 --> 00:02:41,600
We ran a full verification sweep — push tests, health checks, port validation.

45
00:02:41,600 --> 00:02:43,012
Clean.

46
00:02:43,012 --> 00:02:46,462
The biggest build was the network nervous system.

47
00:02:46,462 --> 00:02:53,625
A skill file documenting every infrastructure rule — port allocation, Tailscale routing, firewall configuration.

48
00:02:53,625 --> 00:03:05,712
Then a monitoring daemon running every five minutes, checking seven categories: service ports, binding violations, Tailscale health, unexpected listeners, firewall rules, system resources, systemd failures.

49
00:03:05,712 --> 00:03:09,100
The firewall audit justified the whole effort.

50
00:03:09,100 --> 00:03:12,912
Four stale rules for dead projects still allowing traffic.

51
00:03:12,912 --> 00:03:16,687
Five active services with no firewall rules at all.

52
00:03:16,687 --> 00:03:21,612
They worked through Tailscale routing, but defense in depth means the firewall too.

53
00:03:21,612 --> 00:03:25,000
Four deleted, five added, same session.

54
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:29,787
We ran a methodology research sprint — four approaches to agent workflows.

55
00:03:29,787 --> 00:03:35,662
Superpowers, TDD Guard, Spec Kit from GitHub, Microsoft's Governance Toolkit.

56
00:03:35,662 --> 00:03:38,962
Came back with 16 concrete improvements.

57
00:03:38,962 --> 00:03:44,150
Best steal: plans should be "followable by an agent with zero project context.

58
00:03:44,150 --> 00:03:47,312
Hand it to a fresh agent with no history.

59
00:03:47,312 --> 00:03:50,950
If it can't execute, the plan isn't good enough.

60
00:03:51,150 --> 00:03:57,950
And somewhere in the middle, we researched, wrote, and published a full podcast episode about agent verification.

61
00:03:57,900 --> 00:04:02,875
692 words, 30 percent cut, five minutes of audio.

62
00:04:02,875 --> 00:04:07,162
That episode was about building a babysitter for AI agents.

63
00:04:07,162 --> 00:04:11,675
This one is about building the workshop where those babysitters get trained.

64
00:04:11,675 --> 00:04:13,650
Two things to build.

65
00:04:13,650 --> 00:04:17,650
One: semantic compliance for our verification script.

66
00:04:17,650 --> 00:04:21,712
Right now it checks structure — commits, files, pushes.

67
00:04:21,712 --> 00:04:27,225
Next level is semantics — given the task and the diff, did the agent do what was asked?

68
00:04:27,225 --> 00:04:29,850
Deterministic layer stays.

69
00:04:29,850 --> 00:04:32,875
LLM evaluation goes on top.

70
00:04:32,875 --> 00:04:36,087
Two: per-project constitution files.

71
00:04:36,087 --> 00:04:38,400
From GitHub's Spec Kit.

72
00:04:38,400 --> 00:04:42,962
Each project gets non-negotiable quality standards for that codebase.

73
00:04:42,962 --> 00:04:46,100
Not generic rules — specific ones.

74
00:04:46,100 --> 00:04:49,600
This project requires screenshot validation.

75
00:04:49,600 --> 00:04:52,275
Auth paths need test coverage.

76
00:04:52,275 --> 00:04:55,412
The prompt generator auto-includes them.

77
00:04:55,412 --> 00:04:59,262
Standards become structural, not aspirational.

78
00:04:59,262 --> 00:05:02,737
System throughput isn't how fast the workers go.

79
00:05:02,737 --> 00:05:08,637
It's the quality of the tools, clarity of instructions, and reliability of verification.

80
00:05:08,637 --> 00:05:11,575
Yesterday we upgraded all three.

81
00:05:11,575 --> 00:05:14,062
No user saw a difference.

82
00:05:14,062 --> 00:05:16,875
Everything forward will be faster.

83
00:05:16,875 --> 00:05:18,887
That's The Mega Day.

84
00:05:18,887 --> 00:05:20,537
I'm Jake.

85
00:05:20,537 --> 00:05:22,912
Catch you next episode.

